title: internal/cli: update grpc/protobuf dependency
body:
as a developer I'd like to remove this dependency completely, although it is easier to update it. in the updated version (github.com/JekaMas/go-grpc-net-conn) the code doesn't depend on

```
google.golang.org/grpc
google.golang.org/protobuf
```

only tests depend on this packages. So it's safe to update grpc and protobuf as well.

also introduced generics instead of interfaces to have stronger type checks.

title: Unexpected trx hashes in eth_getTransactionReceiptsByBlock
body:
#### System information

Geth version: `0.2.14-stable-28963d5c`
OS & Version: Linux
Commit hash : 28963d5ccd3028e0ac6f1915845c747862d649d1
eth_getTransactionReceiptsByBlock with params: ["0x1cfe800"]

#### Expected behaviour
All transaction hashes exist in receipt objects

#### Actual behaviour
First receipt:
    "transactionHash": "0x615141657f68a41c33ae2ed087f38782812e1fc386aea0b8a51a88fbd0e86d47",
    "transactionIndex": "0x0"
Second receipt:
   "transactionHash": "0x615141657f68a41c33ae2ed087f38782812e1fc386aea0b8a51a88fbd0e86d47",
    "transactionIndex": "0x1"
Indexes are different, but hashes are the same

And in all receipts indexes are different, but hash only one.

Full response: [receipts.txt](https://github.com/maticnetwork/bor/files/9070408/receipts.txt)
#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour
curl --location --request POST 'NODE_URL' \r
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \r
--data-raw '{
   "jsonrpc": "2.0",
   "id": 1,
   "method": "eth_getTransactionReceiptsByBlock",
   "params": ["0x1cfe800"]
}'

I am writing to you on behalf of the [WatchData.io](https://watchdata.io) (blockchain data provider). We are adding polygon to our system now and this bug is important for us.

title: RFC35/Common Ancestor: Modifying the forkchoice rule
body:
This PR is the second step towards reducing reorgs and is a part of [RFC35](https://www.notion.so/polygontechnology/RFC-35-9f23b1ad5410451792e413640ffffca9). Refer https://github.com/maticnetwork/bor/pull/386 for the first step. 

It adds more functionality to the previously added checkpoint whitelist service. It performs some additional checks during the chain insertion process. The forkchoice module is responsible for checking against any incoming chain if we need to reorg or not using the `ReorgNeeded` function. It basically compared the total difficulty of the local chain and remote incoming chain. This PR adds some additional prevention by introducing a `ValidateReorg` which calls the checkpoint whitelist service to validate the chain. Some important validations are given below. 

- Past chain (where all blocks are <= last current block) case: check the chain against our local whitelist entry. 
- Future chain (where all blocks are > last current block) case: only accept a chain of some specific length (This number is fixed to 256 for now but will be made configurable later on). 

A minor modification over last iteration is that we now fetch N (latest) checkpoint entries instead of 1 in the first run to handle some sync cases for the client. Later on, the subsequent iterations only fetch 1 (latest) entry from heimdall. 

This will ideally prevent the node to get reorged to some wrong/invalid fork and will maintain consistency. Sufficient unit tests are added and devnet testing has been carried on for the same.
